<b><font size=+1>
List:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2">namedroppers</a>
Subject:    <a href="?t=95837887100039&r=1&w=2">Query on fate of host nicknames</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837692300001&r=1&w=2">Rich Wales &lt;wales () UCLA-LOCUS ! ARPA&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198506">1985-06-25 13:48:06</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426482&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426482&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

I assume the following statements are true.  If they aren't, I hope
someone knowledgeable will speak up and correct my misconceptions.

(1) I assume the deadlines in RFC921 are still good (July 15 for conver-
    sion to the domain data base system; September 15 for phaseout of
    the NIC host name table).

(2) In those cases where hosts have new domain names in addition to the
    old ".ARPA" names (e.g., "LOCUS.UCLA.EDU" and "UCLA-LOCUS.ARPA"), I
    assume that both names will exist in the domain data base, at least
    for a while (probably by having the ".ARPA" name entry be a CNAME RR
    pointing to the new domain name entry).

    Assuming the above is true, how long will the extra ".ARPA" names
    be retained in the data base?

(3) I assume that the non-domain "nicknames" currently in the host name
    table will NOT be entered into the domain data base.  (This would
    include all the old "official names" without the ".ARPA" suffix --
    such as "UCLA-LOCUS".)

    Hence, after July 15, I assume that no host will be either required
    or expected to recognize or accept any non-domain "nickname" for any
    host -- since such nicknames will not be in the domain data base.

    In particular, I assume that if any host continues after July 15 to
    use one of its old non-domain "nicknames" (such as the obsolete
    ".ARPA"-less form of its name) in the return addresses ("From:"
    lines) of mail it generates, the users of that host may not reason-
    ably expect anyone else to be able to reply to their mail any more.

    Assuming the above is true, is the NIC planning to take all of the
    non-domain "nicknames" out of the host name table after July 15 --
    leaving only the new domain names and the ".ARPA" names?

-- Rich

